<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
HOUSE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE OUSTS CHAIRMAN OF IMMIGRATION PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The House Judiciary Committee, in a rare move, today ousted the chairman of its 
immigration subcommittee, veteran Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli (D-Ky.) in favor of 
fourth-term Rep. Bruce A. Morrison (D-Conn.). 
</P>
<P>
Mazzoli, a 10-term congressman from Louisville who headed the subcommittee for 
eight years, authored with Sen. Alan K. Simpson (R-Wyo.) the sweeping 
Simpson-Mazzoli immigration reform of 1986. Democratic discontent with Mazzoli 
had been growing over the way he ran the panel, according to Morrison. Mazzoli 
was ousted on a 16-5 secret ballot of Democratic members. Morrison, who was 
next in line of seniority, was voted in 21 to 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
