<HEADLINE>
<P>
RACIAL SLURS REMOVED AT LINCOLN HOME SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SPRINGFIELD, Ill. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Racial slurs and obscenities spray-painted earlier this week on two buildings 
and a fence at the Lincoln Home National Historic Site have been removed, 
officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Pink and blue fluorescent paint was sprayed on the carriage house behind 
Lincoln's home, an adjacent shed and a white wooden fence behind the shed. 
Meters and an air conditioner also were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
Because the damage occurred on federal property, the FBI was investigating, 
acting site Supt. Larry Blake said. No arrests have been made. 
</P>
<P>
The Lincoln home, the only house the nation's 16th President ever owned, was 
reopened last year after a multimillion-dollar renovation. 
</P>
