<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
COACH DENIES DRUG-TEST CHEATING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MONTREAL 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Canadian national weightlifting coach Andrzej Kulesza denied today that he 
supplied urine to four Canadian weightlifters in a bid to cheat in drug tests 
before last year's Seoul Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, former team member Jacques Demers told a federal inquiry into 
drugs in amateur sport that he was told Kulesza and former assistant coach 
Raphael Zuffellato had provided "clean" urine to athletes in danger of testing 
positive for anabolic steroids. 
</P>
<P>
"There are two sides of the story," said Kulesza, interviewed during a break in 
inquiry proceedings today. "(Wednesday) was Jacques' story. When it's my 
chance, I will tell my story." 
</P>
<P>
The attempt to mask the fact that the athletes were taking steroids was 
unsuccessful and the four were caught. Demers' testimony was admitted despite 
objections by lawyers that it was based on hearsay. 
</P>
<P>
Kulesza's lawyer, Joel Silcoff, who cross-examined Demers today, said his 
client will appear before the inquiry next week and will deny Demers' charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
